{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ea222522-c437-4e52-a053-fb9a1a0d02df","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to speedscope format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a [sidecar/ephemeral container](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#collect-using-an-ephemeral-container) or copy the tool binary in.\n- For richer OS-level data (off-CPU, native frames), use `dotnet-counters` to confirm high CPU first, then `perf record` or `dotnet-trace` with `--clreventlevel verbose`.\n- Set `export DOTNET_EnableDiagnostics=1` if diagnostics are disabled.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d8bfada2-62a8-4290-aedd-92b68f4fc66d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":370,"requestId":"C3C4:27C37:1DD5BDE:2178930:6A07C385"},"id":"ea7901c8-e655-4205-a0e4-3e67a987446f","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:08:30.494Z","parentId":"43138d26-863d-4c4b-b5e3-b84f4717a23e"}
